            "response_type": "text",
            "selection_policy": "sequential"
          }
        ]
      },
      "metadata": {},
      "conditions": "#General_Greetings",
      "dialog_node": "node_5_1563740141241",
      "previous_sibling": "Welcome"
    },
    {
      "type": "standard",
      "output": {
        "generic": [
          {
            "values": [
              {
                "text": "The PMFBY Scheme shall be implemented on an ‘Area Approach basis’ i.e., Defined Areas for each notified crop. Defined Area i.e. the Unit Area of Insurance can be a Geo-Fenced/Geo-mapped region having homogeneous Risk Profile for the notified crop."
              }
            ],
            "response_type": "text",
            "selection_policy": "sequential"
          }
        ]
      },
      "metadata": {},
      "conditions": "@notified_area || @notified_crop && @details",
      "dialog_node": "node_7_1563741961899",
      "previous_sibling": "node_6_1563740378911"
    },
    {
      "type": "standard",
      "output": {
        "generic": [
          {
            "values": [
              {
                "text": "All farmers growing notified crops in a notified area during the season who have insurable interest in the crop are eligible. <br><br> All farmers availing Seasonal Agricultural Operations (SAO) loans from Financial Institutions (i.e. loanee farmers) for the notified crop(s) would be covered compulsorily. <br><br>The Scheme would be optional for the non-loanee farmers."
              }
            ],
            "response_type": "text",
            "selection_policy": "sequential"
          }
        ]
      },
      "metadata": {},
      "conditions": "#Criteria_crop_insurance",
      "dialog_node": "node_6_1563740378911",
      "previous_sibling": "node_4_1563738547030"
    },
    {
      "type": "standard",
      "output": {
        "generic": [
          {
            "values": [
              {
                "text": "Following stages of the crop and risks leading to crop loss are covered under the scheme.\n\nPrevented Sowing/ Planting Risk:\nInsured area is prevented from sowing/ planting due to deficit rainfall or adverse seasonal conditions\nStanding Crop (Sowing to Harvesting):\nComprehensive risk insurance is provided to cover yield losses due to non- preventable risks, viz. Drought, Dry spells, Flood, Inundation, Pests and Diseases, Landslides, Natural Fire and Lightening, Storm, Hailstorm, Cyclone, Typhoon, Tempest, Hurricane and Tornado.\nPost-Harvest Losses:\ncoverage is available only up to a maximum period of two weeks from harvesting for those crops which are allowed to dry in cut and spread condition in the field after harvesting against specific perils of cyclone and cyclonic rains and unseasonal rains.\nLocalized Calamities:\nLoss/ damage resulting from occurrence of identified localized risks of hailstorm, landslide, and Inundation affecting isolated farms in the notified area.\n"
              }
            ],
            "response_type": "text",
            "selection_policy": "sequential"
          }
        ]
      },
      "metadata": {},
      "conditions": "#Coverage_enquiry",
      "dialog_node": "node_8_1563742997904",
      "previous_sibling": "node_7_1563741961899"
    },
    {
      "type": "standard",
      "output": {
        "generic": [
          {
            "values": [
              {
                "text": "The Pradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana (Prime Minister's Crop Insurance Scheme) was launched by Prime Minister of India Narendra Modi on 13 February 2016. It envisages a uniform premium of only 2 per cent to be paid by farmers for Kharif crops, and 1.5 per cent for Rabi crops. The premium for annual commercial and horticultural crops will be 5 per cent. <br><br>Objective:\nPradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana (PMFBY) aims at supporting sustainable production in agriculture sector by way of -\n\na) Providing financial support to farmers suffering crop loss/damage arising out of unforeseen events\n\nb) Stabilizing the income of farmers to ensure their continuance in farming\n\nc) Encouraging farmers to adopt innovative and modern agricultural practices\n\nd) Ensuring flow of credit to the agriculture sector; which will contribute to food security, crop diversification and enhancing growth and competitiveness of agriculture sector besides protecting farmers from production risks."
              }
            ],
            "response_type": "text",
            "selection_policy": "sequential"
          }
        ]
      },
